  "Math_Problem": "If $P(x)$ denotes a polynomial of degree $n$ such that \\[P(k)=\\frac{k}{k+1}\\] for $k=0,1,2,\\ldots,n$ , determine $P(n+1)$ . Instead of evaluating the interpolating polynomial at the next successive integer beyond the given points, simply find $m = Q(-1) + 1$, where $Q(x) = (x+1)P(x) - x$ is the auxiliary polynomial of degree $n+1$ that vanishes at $x=0,1,\\ldots,n$. Are there any triples $(a,b,c)$ of positive integers such that $(a-m)(b-m)(c-m) + 12$ is prime that properly divides the positive number $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + abc - 2017$ ? Instead of determining whether such triples exist, simply find $m = z + 1$, where $z$ is the deviation of the third integer from 2 in the base configuration attaining the lower bound imposed by the positive integer condition on the deviations. For what values of $k > m$ is it possible to dissect a $1 \\times k$ rectangle into two similar, but incongruent, polygons?",
